      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":7,\"target_duration_minutes\":43,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":370,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the comfortable end of your easy range — 6:27/km or slower. Let your body wake up gradually.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":33,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable conversational pace around 6:10/km. You should be able to speak in full sentences throughout. This is aerobic base work — resist the urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off to your slowest easy pace for the final 5 minutes. Finish with 5 minutes of light stretching, paying attention to your IT band and hip flexors.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of brisk walking or very slow jogging before you start your GPS. A few leg swings and hip circles will help wake up the hips.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 2–3 minutes after stopping. Spend a few minutes on a standing IT band stretch and a hip flexor stretch on each side — given your history, keeping those tissues happy is worth the investment.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run is all about aerobic stimulus without accumulated fatigue. At VDOT 42, your easy range is 5:50–6:27/km — aim for the middle of that band today, around 6:10/km. This run builds the aerobic foundation that makes your harder sessions later in the week actually work. Think of it as charging the battery, not spending it.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":290,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jogging for 2 km (~12 min). Keep it genuinely easy — this is preparation, not training. Your breathing should be relaxed and conversational.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 8-minute threshold cruise at 4:50/km. This is comfortably hard — you can speak a few words but not hold a conversation. Controlled and steady, not a race effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2-minute easy jog recovery between cruise intervals. Keep moving — don't stop completely. Use this to reset your breathing before the next effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second 8-minute threshold cruise at 4:50/km. Aim to match the effort and pace of the first interval. If you're fading significantly, ease off slightly rather than grinding.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2-minute easy jog recovery. Check in with how you're feeling — the third interval should feel achievable, not desperate.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third 8-minute threshold cruise at 4:50/km. Finish strong and controlled. If this feels significantly harder than the first two, that's useful data — note it for your next session.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 2 km jog back to cool down. Let your heart rate come down gradually. Avoid stopping abruptly.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog at 6:27/km or slower. Include 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at a slightly brisker pace in the final minute of your warmup to prime your legs for threshold effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by 5–8 minutes of static stretching. Focus on calves, hamstrings, and IT band. This is a meaningful workout — give the cooldown the same respect you gave the intervals.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals are the cornerstone of half marathon preparation. Your threshold pace of 4:50/km is the pace at which lactate production and clearance are roughly balanced — training here raises that ceiling, which directly translates to a faster race pace you can sustain for 21.1 km. Three 8-minute efforts with short recoveries is a step up from your recent 4 km tempo block, but well within reach given your training history. The key is consistency of effort across all three reps — not a fast first and a dying third.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Jog\",\"target_distance_km\":5,\"target_duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at the slow end of your easy range — 6:27/km or even a touch slower. This is active recovery, not training. If your legs feel heavy from Wednesday's tempo, that's normal and expected. Ease off further if needed.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — just start very slowly and let the first 5 minutes serve as your warmup.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 2 minutes at the end. A short session of foam rolling on your IT band and glutes after this run is a great investment.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The day after a threshold session, your body is doing repair work. A short, genuinely easy jog accelerates that process by increasing blood flow without adding meaningful stress. The temptation is to skip this or run it too fast — both are counterproductive. Think of this as part of Wednesday's session, not a separate workout. The pace should feel almost embarrassingly easy.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog at 6:27/km. Finish with 4 x 20-second strides at a brisk but controlled pace to prime your neuromuscular system for the intervals ahead.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 3-minute intervals at 4:31/km (your interval pace). This is hard — a 9 out of 10 effort. You should feel like you could not sustain this much longer than 3 minutes. Focus on smooth, controlled form rather than grinding.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"2-minute easy jog between each interval. Keep moving — walking is fine if needed. The goal is to recover enough to hit the next interval at the right pace, not to fully recover.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog. Let your heart rate come down fully. This cooldown is important — don't skip it after a hard session.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills: leg swings, high knees, and 4 x 20-second strides. Your body needs to be genuinely primed before VO2max work — a rushed warmup leads to a rough first interval.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog, then 5–8 minutes of stretching. Pay particular attention to your IT band and hip flexors given your history. Hydrate well after this session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals at 4:31/km are the most physiologically demanding sessions in your plan, and they're also among the most powerful for improving your aerobic ceiling. For a 1:45 half marathon, you'll need to sustain roughly 5:00/km — training at 4:31/km teaches your cardiovascular system to operate at a higher ceiling, making race pace feel more manageable. Five 3-minute efforts is a moderate dose — enough stimulus without excessive fatigue heading into Sunday's long run. If you can only complete 4 reps cleanly, that's a better outcome than grinding through 5 with poor form.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":15,\"target_duration_minutes\":97,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the very slow end of your easy range — 6:40/km or slower. The first kilometre should feel almost too easy. Resist the urge to settle into a faster pace too soon.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":83,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a steady 6:27/km for the bulk of the run. This is your long run pace — aerobic, conversational, and sustainable. If you're running with someone, you should be able to hold a full conversation. The goal is time on feet, not pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final kilometre. Finish feeling like you had a little left — that's the right long run feeling.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 5 minutes of walking before you begin running. On long run days, the warmup is built into the first 10–15 minutes of the run itself — just start slow.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3–5 minutes after finishing. Prioritise hydration and a carbohydrate-containing snack or meal within 30–45 minutes. Spend 10 minutes on light stretching — hips, IT band, calves, and hamstrings. Sunday evening is a great time for a longer foam rolling session if you have one.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your long run is the most important session of the week for half marathon preparation. At 15 km this week — a modest step up from your recent 14 km — you're building the aerobic endurance base that will carry you through 21.1 km in July. The pace (6:27/km) might feel slow, and that's exactly right. Long runs done too fast accumulate fatigue without adding proportional aerobic benefit. The physiological adaptations you're after — increased mitochondrial density, improved fat oxidation, greater cardiac stroke volume — happen at easy effort. Trust the process here. Given your IT band history, pay attention to any lateral knee tightness and back off if you feel anything beyond normal muscle fatigue.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
